As we can see above, out of the six test cases, all but one (`窶廡窶・`) was successful. In the successful cases, Shift-JIS (codepage 932) seemed to result in the correct &quot;original&quot; byte sequence for UTF8.

Getting the Shift-JIS bytes for `窶廡窶・` yields: `E2 80 9C 46 E2 80 81 45`.
`E2 80 9C` coincides with the [UTF8 bytes for left double quotation mark](https://www.utf8-chartable.de/unicode-utf8-table.pl?start=8192&amp;number=128), which is correct. However, `E2 80 81` is `em quad` in UTF8, not the `right double quotation mark` I am expecting. Reinterpreting the whole byte sequence in UTF8 results in `“F EType`

